rs</i> or <i>De Villiers</i> was Nicolas-Antoine Coulon, <i>sieur/chevalier</i> de Villiers, from France, who arrived in QC in 1703. In 1705, he married Angélique Jarret de Verchères. He was an officer in the French army. His descendants also bear altered forms of the surname, such as <i>Devillers</i> and <i>Devillier</i>, and also the surname   Jumonville  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Villiers","meanings":["French and English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Villiers, the name of several places in France, all named from Late Latin <i>villare</i> ‘(part of an) outlying farm, dependent settlement’ (see   Villars  ). Compare   Devilliers  ."]},{"name":"Devillier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Cecile, Jacques, Maudry, Raoul.","French: variant of   Devilliers   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this.","History: The (majority of the) American bearers of the surname <i>Devillier</i> are descendants of Nicolas-Antoine Coulon, <i>sieur</i> de Villiers, from France (see   Devilliers  )."]},{"name":"Jumonville","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alcee, Jean-Paul, Marcel.","French: topographic name shortened from the title <i>sieur de Jumonville</i>, which refers to Jumeauville, a place in Yvelines. The surname <i>Jumonville</i> is not found in France.","History: Joseph Coulon de Villiers, <i>sieur</i> de Jumonville, a son of Nicolas-Antoine Coulon, <i>sieur</i> de Villiers, from France (see   Devilliers  ), married Marie-Marguerite Soumande in Montreal, QC, in 1745."]}]},{"name":"Haymer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","variant of   Hamer  .","variant of <b>Aymer</b> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>, from the Middle English personal name <i>Aimar</i>, found in <i>Domesday Book</i> as one of the forms of the Old English name <i>Æthelmǣr</i>. Alternatively, the Middle English personal name could also be via Old French from an ancient Germanic personal name, either <i>Agimar</i> or <i>(H)adamar</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Hamer","meanings":["form of the name of the Greek epic poet <i>Homēros</i>, now regularly used as a given name in the United States (  compare  Virgil  ), where it has been immortalized by the cartoon character Homer Simpson in the television series The Simpsons. Many theories have been put forward to explain the origin of the name of the poet, but none is conclusive. It is identical in form with the Greek vocabulary word <i>homēros</i> ‘hostage’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Haymer d’Villiers was born about 1120, in Normandy, France. She married Haymer d'Avillers about 1141, in Normandy, France. They were the parents of at least 4 sons."},"et":{"about 1120–":"umbes 1120–Surnud","1116–Male":"1116–Surnud","1142–Male":"1142–Surnud","1144–Male":"1144–Surnud","1146–Male":"1146–Surnud","1148–Male":"1148–Surnud","1120–Female":"1120–Surnud","1116":"1116","1148":"1148","1146":"1146","1144":"1144","about 1148":"umbes 1148","1120":"1120","1142":"1142","about 1146":"umbes 1146","Cir 1142":"1142","about 1144":"umbes 1144","about 1141":"umbes 1141","about 1120":"umbes 1120","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 1120–":"noin 1120–Kuollut","1116–Male":"1116–Kuollut","1142–Male":"1142–Kuollut","1144–Male":"1144–Kuollut","1146–Male":"1146–Kuollut","1148–Male":"1148–Kuollut","1120–Female":"1120–Kuollut","1116":"1116","1148":"1148","1146":"1146","1144":"1144","about 1148":"noin 1148","1120":"1120","1142":"1142","about 1146":"noin 1146","Cir 1142":"1142","about 1144":"noin 1144","about 1141":"noin 1141","about 1120":"noin 1120","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Ranska","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Ranska"},"fr":{"about 1120–":"environ 1120–Décédée","1116–Male":"1116–Décédé","1142–Male":"1142–Décédé","1144–Male":"1144–Décédé","1146–Male":"1146–Décédé","1148–Male":"1148–Décédé","1120–Female":"1120–Décédée","1116":"1116","1148":"1148","1146":